There will be a lot more to magic.</a><a href="https://twitter.com/IAPonomarenko/status/1630621272446058517?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">5:29 PM ∙ Feb 28, 20239,126Likes603Retweets</a><p>The attack summarizes much of this Russian campaign in a nutshell, and why I would argue it represents both a failure of Russian military learning and a failing campaign at the same time. Its designed to be spectacular, but reveals Russia does not possess either the equipment or planning capacity to execute the campaign successfully (btw, I do promise I will get to the mid-week, deep-dive update on this campaign as an example of military learning soon). The reasons for the shortcomings/failings briefly are as follows:</p><ol><li><p>Timing. Since February 1 there have been only three such attacks. This is ludicrously too few to significantly shut down Ukrainian power generation. What these attacks show is that making effective attacks on infrastructure targets requires constant repetition, to make sure the targets are taken out of action for long periods—every few weeks is not enough. And guess what—here we are a few days after the attack and the power is mostly back on (completely it seems in Kyiv). </p><a href="https://twitter.com/KyivIndependent/status/1634589883892113411?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_Hgeu8TbeVnx8F7_JdgaMX25EpPcf4rGtt0sdcqSBxs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvS3lpdkluZGVwZW5kZW50LmpwZw==" alt="Twitter avatar for @KyivIndependent" loading="lazy"/>The Kyiv Independent @KyivIndependent⚡️Power restored in Kyiv but 5% of residents still without heating after Russian attack.

Power supply was restored to all Kyiv residents on March 11 after some districts were hit with interruptions related to Russia&#39;s mass attack 2 days prior, the Kyiv administration said.</a><a href="https://twitter.com/KyivIndependent/status/1634589883892113411?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">4:19 PM ∙ Mar 11, 2023949Likes161Retweets</a></li><li><p>Lack of Russian planning or equipment: What these attacks show is that either Russian planning is in the worst shape possible (they have enough platforms to fight the campaign, but cant seem to orchestrate attacks more than once every two weeks or so) or they lack the platforms to make the attacks more often. The motley collection of platforms that they are using, including re-purposed anti-air missiles such as the S-300, make the latter most likely. Russia started this campaign without the equipment to carry it off, but instead of recognizing the reality of their situation, they continue with these sporadic, uncoordinated missile tantrums, using up what stockpiles they do have and what top of the line-equipment is available to them, for increasingly little result. This is typified by the use of the Kinzhals this week—now they use them? 4-5 months after the campaign started, and the Ukrainians have adjusted, they finally throw their most effective kit into action. And now, three days later, they dont follow up? The shortcomings are obvious.</p></li><li><p>Ukrainian adaptation. This Russian missile campaign seems almost ideally planned to help Ukraine learn and adjust. By making a mass attack on Ukrainian power, but then not following up for weeks, the Russian both stress the Ukrainian power system greatly, but also provide the Ukrainians time to learn how to repair and protect their systems before the Russians come back. And guess what—the Ukrainians have learned. They now clearly have strong protocols about how to prepare for and react to these attacks, and are able to get power restored to most people relatively quickly. At the same time, the Russians have provided impetus for the supporters of Ukraine to send both many new advanced anti-air systems to Ukraine and to provide Ukraine with extra power-generation systems.</p></li></ol><p>I cant go into it in much more detail during this update—but the attack this week is a sign of Russian strategic and military failure.</p><p><strong>Bakhmut</strong></p><p>Ive been writing a great deal about the Battle of Bakhmut during the past weeks, and the situation and debates are basically the same. The Ukrainian government has decided to stay in the exposed city and continue the fight against the Russians who seem obsessed with the idea of seizing Bakhmut. I wrote a more detailed substack this week on what I assumed was the Ukrainian strategy. </p><a href="https://twitter.com/PhillipsPOBrien/status/1633593671621783561?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/qFXyZjbPE4Q9yDxAj494bDXnZgorU668l07dwLSv1mw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvUGhpbGxpcHNQT0JyaWVuLmpwZw==" alt="Twitter avatar for @PhillipsPOBrien" loading="lazy"/>Phillips P. OBrien @PhillipsPOBrienJust sent out my midweek substack update for subscribers. Tried to explain why Ukraine is fighting for Bakhmut, even when their forces are in what looks like a precarious position. </a><a href="https://phillipspobrien.substack.com/p/why-bakhmut-a-guesstimate-of-ukrainian?utm_source=twitter&amp;sd=pf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux." loading="lazy"/>phillipspobrien.substack.comWhy Bakhmut? A Guesstimate of Ukrainian StrategyBakhmut doesnt matter--the coming Ukrainian offensive really does.</a><a href="https://twitter.com/PhillipsPOBrien/status/1633593671621783561?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">10:20 PM ∙ Mar 8, 2023499Likes58Retweets</a><p>It was interesting to see that in the last two days, the Ukrainian government has come out and basically said that this is their strategy. </p><a href="https://twitter.com/PhillipsPOBrien/status/1634664025408651267?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/qFXyZjbPE4Q9yDxAj494bDXnZgorU668l07dwLSv1mw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvUGhpbGxpcHNQT0JyaWVuLmpwZw==" alt="Twitter avatar for @PhillipsPOBrien" loading="lazy"/>Phillips P. OBrien @PhillipsPOBrienWell here is by far the clearest articulation of the Ukrainian government&#39;s case for continuing to fight at Bakhmut. An interview by @Podolyak_M given to the Italian paper La Stampa, summarized here. </a><a href="https://www.kyivpost.com/post/14119" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/iCQtwc3v9XGC6eV6yM83Ey89gvNhMMMBOF_rpzUaNww=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd182MDAsaF8zMTQsY19maWxsLGZfYXV0byxxX2F1dG86Z29vZCxmbF9wcm9ncmVzc2l2ZTpzdGVlcC9odHRwcyUzQSUyRiUyRnN1YnN0YWNrLXBvc3QtbWVkaWEuczMuYW1hem9uYXdzLmNvbSUyRnB1YmxpYyUyRmltYWdlcyUyRjdiNzllZWM4LTM2YmMtNDQ4OS04YTU0LTZlNWFkYzEyZDBmYV8xMjAweDY4Ni5qcGVn" loading="lazy"/>kyivpost.comUkraine’s Counteroffensive Will Start in Two Months, Zelensky’s Aide SaysMykhailo Podolyak said Ukraine’s continued defense of Bakhmut has two goals: to inflict heavy losses on the Russian army, and to gain time for a counteroffensive.</a><a href="https://twitter.com/PhillipsPOBrien/status/1634664025408651267?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">9:14 PM ∙ Mar 11, 2023836Likes156Retweets</a><p>This strategy is, I would argue, consistent within the intellectual framework by which the Ukrainian government has fought the war. They basically have tried to exhaust, or cause so much attrition to Russian forces that when Ukraine attempts to liberate areas, the Russian forces lack the combat power, logistics and figthing morale to hold them off. With the Ukrainians preparing for the largest, most complex offensive they have ever attempted this Spring/Summer, their need to wear down the Russians beforehand is even more extreme. And the last thing they want, as I tried to point out in the substack, is for the Russians to take Bakhmut, declare victory, and then dig Russian forces into prepared defensive positions to be rested and resupplied before the Ukrainian attack.</p><p>Of course this strategy is also relentless for the Ukrainians, who have had to endure so much. Witnessing the constant fighting around Bakhmut while all the time they see the Russians treat their fellow Ukrainians with bloody cruelty has to take an enormous psychological toll. This week also had a number of events that would have emphasized that toll. First was the war-crime execution of this Ukrainian soldier, which the Russians taped and then showed around.</p><a href="https://twitter.com/IAPonomarenko/status/1632753888074907650?s=20" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/EDb74EPeQgzxZOozCAcDK9xmBq9cNml7RKGHgE2dGQM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvSUFQb25vbWFyZW5rby5qcGc=" alt="Twitter avatar for @IAPonomarenko" loading="lazy"/>Illia Ponomarenko 🇺🇦 @IAPonomarenkoExecuted by Russians.
